<h1>General Orders</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationRight">Head Quarters, New York, May 2nd 1776.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
<table class="password"><tr>
		<td class="parole">Parole Granby.</td>
		<td class="csigns">Countersign Wilkes</td>
	      </tr></table>

</div>
<p>The first, second, and fourth Brigades, to encamp to morrow in the forenoon; each Regiment to be drawn up on their regimental Parade, at eight OClock in the Morning, and directly march to the Ground, markd out for their Encampment, when they are immediately to pitch their tentsThe Qr Mr General will provide Camp-Equipage, Wood, and Straw, necessary for the Encampment.</p>
<p>The Brigadiers General, or Officers commanding, will attend to the Encampment of their respective Brigades, and see that one Regiment does not encroach upon another, but encamps exactly upon the Ground assigned.</p>
<p>The Chief Engineer Lieut. Col. Putnam, to send every evening the Details for the working Parties wanted for the next day, to Major Genl Putnam, who will provide Boats, and give the necessary Orders for marching them to the places where they are to work, and will also direct, the entrenching Tools to be properly distributed.</p>
<p>Corporal John Weaver, of Capt. Williams Independent Company of Rifflemen,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0149-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0149-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> tried at a late General Court Martial, whereof Col. Baldwin was President, for getting drunk, when on duty. The Court find the Prisoner guilty of the Charge, and do sentence him to be reduced to the Ranks, and whipped Thirty Lashes on his bare back.</p>
<p>Jno. McGarra of Capt. Stephensons Independent Company of Riffle-men, tried at the above General Court Martial, for mutinous behaviour, is found guilty by the Court, and sentenced to be whipped Fifteen Lashes on his bare back.</p>
<p>Samuel Londers and Abner Fuller, of Capt. Bissells Company, in Col. Huntingtons Regiment,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0149-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0149-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> tried at the above General
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0184">[184]</span>
Court Martial for DesertionThe Court finding the Prisoners guilty of the Charge, do sentence each of them to receive Thirty Lashes, on his bare back. The General approves of the foregoing Sentences, and orders the execution of them to morrow Morning at Guard mounting.</p>
<p>The General Court Martial, whereof Col: Baldwin is President, is dissolved.</p>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0149-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0149-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0149-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Otho Holland Williams (17491794) of Frederick, Md., joined Capt. Thomas Prices company of Maryland riflemen as a lieutenant in June 1775 and marched to Cambridge with it in July. When Price became major of Col. William Smallwoods Maryland regiment in January 1776, Williams succeeded him as captain of the rifle company. Williams was appointed major of Col. Hugh Stephensons newly organized rifle regiment in June 1776, and at Fort Washington the following November, he was wounded and captured by the enemy. After his exchange in January 1778 Williams took command of the 6th Maryland Regiment, and in January 1781 he became colonel of the 1st Maryland Regiment. In the southern campaigns of 1780 and 1781 Williams proved himself an exceptionally able combat commander. He was promoted to brigadier general in May 1782 and served until January 1783 when he resigned from the army to become naval officer at Baltimore.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0149-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0149-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Captains Ozias Bissell (17311822) and Ebenezer Fitch Bissell (17361814) both commanded companies in Col. Jedediah Huntingtons 17th Continental Regiment. Both men were taken prisoner at the Battle of Long Island in August. <span class="choice addition" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Added &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2012-10-03]]&lt;/span&gt; ]">Samuel Landers and Abner Fuller belonged to Capt. Ebenezer Fitch Bissells company (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Collections of the Connecticut Historical Society&lt;/i&gt;. 31 vols. Hartford, 18601967. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Conn. Hist. Soc. Col.</span></span>, 8:27).</span></p>

</div>
